6 (c) (d) It is a defense to a prosecution under this section:
7 (1) that the accused person:
8 (1) (A) engaged in a reasonable act of training, handling, or
9 discipline; and
10 (2) (B) acted as an employee or agent of a law enforcement
11 agency; or
12 (2) that:
13 (A) the actions of the accused person were objectively
14 reasonable and taken in good faith to protect the person or
15 another individual from imminent injury by the law
16 enforcement animal; and
17 (B) neither the accused person nor the other individual
18 substantially contributed to the circumstances leading to
19 the deployment of the law enforcement animal.
20 (d) (e) In addition to any sentence or fine imposed for a conviction
21 of an offense under this section, the court:
22 (1) may order the person convicted to make restitution to the
23 person or law enforcement agency owning the animal for
24 reimbursement of veterinary bills; and
25 (2) shall order the person convicted to make restitution to the
26 person or law enforcement agency owning the animal for
27 reimbursement of the cost of replacing the animal, which may
28 include the cost of training the animal, if the animal is
29 permanently disabled or killed.
30 SECTION 11. IC 35-46-3-12, AS AMENDED BY P.L.141-2019,
31 SECTION 10, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
32 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 12. (a) This section does not apply to a person
33 who euthanizes an injured, a sick, a homeless, or an unwanted domestic
34 animal if:
35 (1) the person is employed by a humane society, an animal control
36 agency, or a governmental entity operating an animal shelter or
37 other animal impounding facility; and
38 (2) the person euthanizes the domestic animal in accordance with
39 guidelines adopted by the humane society, animal control agency,
40 or governmental entity operating the animal shelter or other
41 animal impounding facility.
42 (b) A person who knowingly or intentionally abuses a vertebrate
EH 1165—LS 6739/DI 150

14
1 animal commits cruelty to an animal, a Class A misdemeanor.
2 However, the offense is a Level 6 felony if:
3 (1) the person has a previous, unrelated conviction under this
4 section; or
5 (2) the person committed the offense with the intent to threaten,
6 intimidate, coerce, harass, or terrorize a family or household
7 member;
8 (3) the offense is committed in the immediate presence of a
9 minor; or
10 (4) the act results in:
11 (A) serious permanent disfigurement;
12 (B) unconsciousness;
13 (C) permanent or protracted loss or impairment of the
14 function of a bodily member or organ; or
15 (D) the death;
16 of the animal.
17 (c) A person who knowingly or intentionally tortures or mutilates a
18 vertebrate animal commits torturing or mutilating a vertebrate animal,
19 a Level 6 felony.
20 (d) As used in this subsection, "domestic animal" means an animal
21 that is not wild. The term is limited to:
22 (1) cattle, calves, horses, mules, swine, sheep, goats, dogs, cats,
23 poultry, ostriches, rhea, and emus; and
24 (2) an animal of the bovine, equine, ovine, caprine, porcine,
25 canine, feline, camelid, cervidae, or bison species.
26 (d) A person who knowingly or intentionally kills a domestic animal
27 without the consent of the owner of the domestic animal commits
28 killing a domestic animal, a Level 6 felony.
29 (e) It is a defense to a prosecution under this section that the
30 accused person:
31 (1) reasonably believes the conduct was necessary to:
32 (A) prevent injury to the accused person or another person;
33 (B) protect the property of the accused person from destruction
34 or substantial damage; or
35 (C) prevent a seriously injured vertebrate animal from
36 prolonged suffering; or
37 (2) engaged in a reasonable and recognized act of training,
38 handling, or disciplining the vertebrate animal.
39 (f) When a court imposes a sentence or enters a dispositional decree
40 under this section, the court:
41 (1) shall consider requiring:
42 (A) a person convicted of an offense under this section; or
EH 1165—LS 6739/DI 150

15
1 (B) a child adjudicated a delinquent child for committing an
2 act that would be a crime under this section if committed by an
3 adult;
4 to receive psychological, behavioral, or other counseling as a part
5 of the sentence or dispositional decree; and
6 (2) may order an individual described in subdivision (1) to receive
7 psychological, behavioral, or other counseling as a part of the
8 sentence or dispositional decree.
9 SECTION 12. IC 35-46-3-12.5, AS AMENDED BY P.L.158-2013,
10 SECTION 567, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS
11 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 12.5. A person who knowingly or
12 intentionally:
13 (1) abuses;
14 (2) abandons;
15 (3) kills; or
16 (4) neglects;
17 a vertebrate animal with the intent to threaten, intimidate, coerce,
18 harass, or terrorize a family or household member commits domestic
19 violence animal cruelty, a Level 6 felony.
